pullsbody:
Fixes #97


As of January 1 2019, Mozilla requires that all GitHub projects include this [CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md](https://github.com/mozilla/repo-templates/blob/master/templates/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md) file in the project root. The file has two parts:

1. Required Text - All text under the headings *Community Participation Guidelines and How to Report*, are required, and should not be altered.
2. Optional Text - The Project Specific Etiquette heading provides a space to speak more specifically about ways people can work effectively and inclusively together. Some examples of those can be found on the [Firefox Debugger](https://github.com/devtools-html/debugger.html/blob/master/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md) project, and [Common Voice](https://github.com/mozilla/voice-web/blob/master/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md). (The optional part is commented out in the [raw template file](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mozilla/repo-templates/blob/master/templates/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md), and will not be visible until you modify and uncomment that part.)

If you have any questions about this file, or Code of Conduct policies and procedures, please see [Mozilla-GitHub-Standards](https://wiki.mozilla.org/GitHub/Repository_Requirements) or email Mozilla-GitHub-Standards+CoC@mozilla.com.

_(Message COC002)_
pull_commit_message:
Add Mozilla Code of Conduct file

Fixes #97.

_(Message COC002)_

pullsbody:
Adds channel administration:
- `element.broadcastChannel` lists the channel name
- `element.setBroadcastChannel(str)` sets the outbound channel name
- `element.subscriptions` is an array of channel/listener pairs
- `element.setSubscription(channel, listener)` adds a new channel/listener pair, or updates an existing one based on listener
- `element.removeSubscription(channel, listener)` removes a subscription.
pull_commit_message: added element.subscriptionListeners, for the list of consuming functions on an element

pulltitle: v1 of shutter and matching snapshot component for standalone testing
pullsbody:
[NOT FOR MERGING, JUST FOR FEEDBACK]

So, I don't quite know why the original customEvent code wasn't working, but in Nightly, it was throwing exceptions.  I _think_ I'm using the newer dom syntax.  Haven't tested in chrome yet though.

Any ideas what may have changed?

the webrtc stuff is straightforward enough.  There's a bunch of discussion to have about what the component should look like etc., but that should be easy.

there are a couple of things about the component code which would be good to tweak:
- not having to do .parentNode.parentNode etc. in the onclick event handler
- having exceptions that don't all point to Ceci.js
- some jquery or equivalent for trivial thigns like addClass/removeClass and more concise syntax (suggestions welcome).

although this does raise questions about two components that generate "the same thing", like a timer emitting <number> on the blue channel, which gets picked up by an amplifier which posts <2*number> to the blue channel, with a consumer listening for "data" on the blue channel. It doesn't know (it does in Ceci, but not in html) who the data came from, just that it's numbers.
